Design classes for easy change

Design classes for easy extensions

Don't guess, if you expect change, prefer design that makes this change easy, if you don't expect any change, learn from the next change 


private pure virtual functions can be overriden in the derived class but cannot be accessed from  the derived class


Data member initialization 

	use uniform initialization for objects of classes 

```cpp
class widget 
{
	int i; 
	std:: string s;
	int * pi;
};

int main ()
{
	widget w1; // default initialization will make i and pi not intitialized (does not initialize fundamental types)
	widget w2{} // uniform initialization will initialize fundamental and user defined types
}
```

adding an empty constructor to this code will result in i and pi to be not initialized again 

```cpp
class widget 
{
	widget(){}
	int i; // uninitialized
	std:: string s; //default
	int * pi;// uninitialized
};

int main ()
{

	widget w2{} 
}

```

	Avoid writing and empty default constructor if you don't have in-class member initializers

	prefer initialization(initializer list) to assignment in the constructor

	Don't repeat youself, avoid duplication


```cpp
// bad
class widget
{
	widget() 
	: i {42} // initialize to 42
	, s {"cpp"} // initialize to cpp
	, pi {} // initialize to nullptr
	{}
	widget (int j)
	: i {j}
	, s {"cpp"} // duplicaion
	, pi {} // duplication

};

// good , use constructore delegatiom
class widget 
{
	widget () : widget (42);
	{

	}
	widget (int j)
	: i {j}
	, s {"cpp"} // duplicaion
	, pi {} // duplication
}
```

>  you could also use in-class member initializers 


```cpp
 class widget 
	{
		widget () =  default;
		widget (int j)
		: i {j}
	int i {42}; // will be used if not explicitly listed in the initializer list
	std::string s{"cpp"};// will be used i

This flow is used to predict the price of a single item based on its specifications and compare it against similar items in a dataset.



```mermaid

graph TD

    A[Start] --> B{Select Price Forecasting};

    B --> C[1. Select Dataset];

    C --> D[2. Select Cost Drivers & Target];

    D --> E[3. Configure Parameters];

    E --> F[4. Configure Exchange Rates];

    F --> G[5. Run Analysis];

    G --> H[View Results];

    H --> I[End];



    subgraph "Step 1: Dataset"

        C;

    end

    subgraph "Step 2: Features"

        D;

    end

    subgraph "Step 3: Configuration"

        E; F;

    end

    subgraph "Step 4: Analysis & Results"

        G; H;

    end

```



1.  **Select Dataset**: The user chooses a product dataset (e.g., Shafts, Capacitors) to work with.

2.  **Select Cost Drivers & Target**: The user selects the columns (features) that are believed to influence the price and sets their relative importance (priority). They also select the target column to predict (e.g., "Unit Price").

3.  **Configure Parameters**: The user inputs the specifications for the target item they want a price for.

4.  **Configure Exchange Rates**: The user selects a reference currency and confirms or adjusts the exchange rates for all currencies present in the dataset.

5.  **Run Analysis**: The frontend sends the configuration to the backend. The backend then finds similar items, trains a model to predict the price, and uses an AI to generate a justification report.

6.  **View Results**: The UI displays the predicted price, a confidence score, and the detailed AI-generated report with a breakdown of comparable items.

This flow is used to analyze an entire dataset to find segments with high price volatility, helping to identify opportunities for cost savings and standardization.



```mermaid

graph TD

    A[Start] --> B{Select Segment Analysis};

    B --> C[1. Select Dataset];

    C --> D[2. Select Grouping Columns & Target];

    D --> E[3. Configure Exchange Rates];

    E --> F[4. Run Analysis];

    F --> G[View Results];

    G --> H[End];



    subgraph "Step 1: Dataset"

        C;

    end

    subgraph "Step 2: Features"

        D;

    end

    subgraph "Step 3: Configuration"

        E;

    end

    subgraph "Step 4: Analysis & Results"

        F; G;

    end

```



1.  **Select Dataset**: The user selects a dataset.

2.  **Select Grouping Columns & Target**: The user chooses a set of columns that define "similar" items. The system will group all items in the dataset by these columns. They also select the price column to analyze.

3.  **Configure Exchange Rates**: The user confirms the exchange rates for currency normalization.

4.  **Run Analysis**: The backend processes the entire dataset, groups items, calculates price variation statistics (mean, std dev, etc.) for each group, and sends a summary report to the LLM.

5.  **View Results**: The UI displays the results in three tabs:

    *   **AI Insights**: A high-level summary from the AI explaining the key drivers of price variation.

    *   **Multiple Grouping**: A detailed, filterable table of all groups containing more than one item.

    *   **Single Items**: A table listing all items that were unique and did not belong to a group.



