Constant member functions in C++ are declared constant to prevent it from modifying any non-static member variables, non [[Mutable member variables C++| mutable]] member variables

i.e. :  Const member functions can only modify :
1 - static member variables 
2 - mutable member variables

anything else will produce an error


```
class myClass
{
	public:
		myClass ()
		{

		}
		void myfucn () const
		{

		}
	private:

}
```

note : to declare a member function as const, the const keyword must come **==after==** the function name , if the const keyword is before the function it means it is returning a const type

