C can converge between int and enum without compilation errors 

```c
typedef enum 
{
    sunday,
    monday
}myenum ;

void func(myenum x )
{
    printf("%d", x);
}   
int main()
{
    func(5);
    return 0;
}

// compiles without errors
```

In C++ however, you have to use static casting otherwise it will generate build errors
```cpp
enum myenum
{
    sunday,
    monday
} ;

void func(myenum x )
{
   cout << x << endl;
}   
int main()
{
	// have to use static_cast or invalid conversion error will be generated
    func(static_cast<myenum>(5));
    return 0;
}

```

```cpp
int x ;  //  not initialized , default value initialization 
int x = 10 OR int x = y;  //  copy initialization
int x(10) ; //  direct initialization

// List initialization
int x {10};  //  direct list initilization //  brace initialization // uniform initialization
int e = {} //  copy list initialization
int f {}; // value initialization
```

- Copy initialization is used when values are implicitly copied, like when passing arguments to  a function by value (because the compiler creates a new variable and  gives it the value of the argument)
- List initialization will produce an error for conversions that produce data loss, i.e : [[Narrowing conversions]] are ill formed
```cpp
int x {4.5} ; // error
```

