This flowchart shows the general journey from the user's perspective.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User selects country and uploads invoices] --> B{Clicks #quot;Generate#quot;};
    B --> C[Frontend shows loading spinner];
    C --> D{Backend processes and calls AI Service};
    D --> E[Backend returns structured data];
    E --> F[Frontend receives data and updates UI];
    F --> G[User sees comparison table and analysis];
```

---

The `UtilityInvoiceAgent.tsx` component orchestrates the API call. It sets the loading state and sends the files to its own backend.

**Code Snippet (`UtilityInvoiceAgent.tsx`):**
This function constructs a `FormData` object and uses the `fetch` API to send a `POST` request.

```javascript
// In UtilityInvoiceAgent.tsx
const runAnalysis = async (tempFiles: File[], selectedCountry: string, prompts: any) => {
    setLoading(true);

    const formData = new FormData();
    tempFiles.forEach((file) => {
        formData.append('files', file);
    });
    formData.append('prompt', prompts[selectedCountry]);
    // ...
    const res = await fetch(`${BASE_URL}/pp/utility-invoices/api/v1alpha1/invoice-analysis`, {
        method: 'POST',
        body: formData,
    });
    // ...
};
```

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A["FastAPI receives POST request"] --> B["Router (`generate_results.py`)"];
    B --> C["Controller (`generation_controller.py`)"];
    C --> D["HTTP Client (`framework_client.py`)"];
    D --> E["External Generation Service"];
    E --> D;
    D --> C;
    C --> B;
    B --> F["FastAPI sends JSON response"];
```

#CPP 

 1- Given the following code 

```cpp
 class Character 
 {
public:
  virtual void Act(Character* Target)
  {
    cout << "Character Acting\n";
  }
};

class Goblin : public Character
{
public:
  void Act(Character* Target)
  {
    cout << "Goblin Acting\n";
  }
};

class Dragon : public Character
{
public:
  void Act(Character* Target)
  {
    cout << "Dragon Acting\n";
  }
};

void Battle(Character* A, Character* B)
{
  A->Act(B);
  B->Act(A);
}
```
 what's the difference between A and B

```cpp
A :
    int main(){

    Goblin * A ;
    Dragon * B ;

    Battle(A, B);

    }


B :

    int main(){

    Goblin * A = new Goblin;
    Dragon * B = new Dragon;

    Battle(A, B);

    }
```

Answer :

A produces a [[Segmentation fault C++|Segmentation fault]] because Pointers do not point to an instance of the variables, and therefore they point to nothing, and when we try to dereference them in Battle function they
cause the segfault.

B works fine .

