**Q1: What is the Rule of Three in C++ and why is it important?**

**A1:** The Rule of Three states that if a class requires a user-defined destructor, copy constructor, or copy assignment operator, it likely needs all three. This rule is crucial for classes that manage resources (e.g., dynamic memory) to ensure proper resource management. Without these functions, you risk issues like memory leaks, double deletions, and shallow copies.

---

**Q2: Explain the Rule of Five and how it extends the Rule of Three. Provide an example.**

**A2:** The Rule of Five extends the Rule of Three to include the move constructor and move assignment operator. This rule helps manage resources efficiently by supporting move semantics, which transfer resources rather than copying them. This prevents unnecessary deep copies and improves performance.

**Example:**

```cpp
class MyClass {
public:
    char* data;

    MyClass(const char* str = nullptr) {
        if (str) {
            data = new char[strlen(str) + 1];
            strcpy(data, str);
        } else {
            data = nullptr;
        }
    }

    ~MyClass() {
        delete[] data;
    }

    MyClass(const MyClass& other) {
        if (other.data) {
            data = new char[strlen(other.data) + 1];
            strcpy(data, other.data);
        } else {
            data = nullptr;
        }
    }

    MyClass& operator=(const MyClass& other) {
        if (this != &other) {
            delete[] data;
            if (other.data) {
                data = new char[strlen(other.data) + 1];
                strcpy(data, other.data);
            } else {
                data = nullptr;
            }
        }
        return *this;
    }

    MyClass(MyClass&& other) noexcept : data(other.data) {
        other.data = nullptr;

